begin_memory_text: At the beginning of the conversation, we talked about where we live and if we did anything over the weekend. We talked about the limit of things there are to do during the pandemic and how hard it is. We talked about travel.
middle_memory_text: In the middle of the conversation we spoke about places we had been or where we would like to travel to. We spoke about what we did for a living and continued the conversation about the pandemic.
end_memory_text: At the end of the conversation, we spoke about my kids and what they are doing and our pets. We talked about our dogs and my turtle and how old they are and about taking care of them right now.
rest_of_day_open: I think the rest of my week will go the same as every day has for the past nine months - because of covid, not much changes. However next weekend, we are going for a drive and I get to see my daughter, who I have not seen in three months. I am excited for that!
critical_positive: My conversation partner was very easy going. She asked open ended questions. We were able to find common ground even though she was younger than me. She had traveled further than I, so it was interesting to learn about the places she had been. If there was a lull in the conversation, we were both able to easily fill it.
critical_negative: The only thing that made it difficult was that there was an age gap, so I am sure it was harder for her to relate to my position in life as my eldest is probably close to her age. Even that was not too much of a challenge as we found plenty of things to talk about.

begin_memory_text: At the beginning we talked about Salem, MA, Halloween and where we were both from
middle_memory_text: We talked about her kids, COVID impact on schools and people and a little about what we both do for a living
end_memory_text: We talked about pets - her turtle and dog - my dog and dispensing Halloween candy
rest_of_day_open: I see my week being kind of a cluster - we are starting a new client, which means I will be very busy. This client is super demanding and this onboarding has already been delayed. I plan on trying to work in more de-stressing activities like yoga, meditation and cooking to offset the trashfire that I can see coming at work.
critical_positive: It definitely seemed like we should talk about more "small talk" stuff rather than deep conversations about personal identities or politics. I think we could tell right off the bat that we did not have a ton in common, so we talked around it with basic stuff like Halloween and COVID.
critical_negative: My partner assumed I was in school which was kind of off-putting, since I'm nearly 30. I asked her what she did for a living, which was also assumptive since she volunteers and is a stay-at-home mom. She tried to hint at politics by just wanting COVID to end, but I had a gut feeling we would not agree.
